<p><strong>10)</strong> Nohup</p>

<p>Pra rodar um comando em background e fazer com que o mesmo fique imune a sinais de hangup, usa-se o comando nohup.
Exemplo de uso:</p>
<div class="language-sh highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">nohup</span> ./comando_que_vai_demorar &amp;
</code></pre></div></div>
<ul>
  <li>Para calcular o tempo do comando:
    <div class="language-sh highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">nohup </span>bash <span class="nt">-c</span> <span class="s2">"(time ./malha_read malhaquad2.msh)"</span> <span class="nt">-print</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> file.out &amp;
<span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">nohup </span>bash <span class="nt">-c</span> <span class="s2">"(time ./malha_read mal</span><span class="se">\l</span><span class="s2">im_{</span><span class="se">\d</span><span class="s2">ot{</span><span class="se">\g</span><span class="s2">amma}</span><span class="se">\r</span><span class="s2">ightarrow 0}haquad2.msh) &amp;&gt; timeuse.txt"</span> &amp;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ul>

<p><em>Tips:</em></p>
<ul>
  <li>http://www.phas.ubc.ca/~mbelab/computer/linux-intro/html/long-calculations.html</li>
  <li>http://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/22992/how-to-limit-the-number-of-lines-a-commands-output-has-available-in-bash</li>
</ul>

